"Abstract Last month, I deviated slightly from my usual theme and reviewed the historical development of the, so-called, Common Criteria. This month, I make no apology for returning to some more familiar topics — the continuing development of UK and US Cryptography Policy from the twin perspectives of law enforcement and export control. Not only have there been further statements about the way forward since my earlier articles (see Parts 5 and 7, in particular), but readers may well find that the positions being articulated in these two countries provide a useful model for how the authorities may react elsewhere. I have also taken this opportunity to record the final chapter in the long-running saga of the EU Digital Signature Directive. In each case, I have edited the official statements for presentational purposes, but otherwise the content is as originally published."
